    <p><strong>2. Inquiry into the Nature of Orientation — ‘niṣhṭhā’:</strong> The word <em>niṣhṭhā</em> implies a settled state or orientation of being. Arjuna is not questioning isolated actions but the underlying condition from which those actions arise. This shifts the focus from external behavior to internal alignment. The question is not whether such worship is right or wrong, but what quality of consciousness it reflects. This introduces a deeper layer of analysis: actions may appear similar externally but differ fundamentally based on the inner state driving them.</p>

